'''Sia Kate Isobelle Furler''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|s|iː|ə|}} {{respell|SEE|ə}}; born 18 December 1975) is an Australian singer and songwriter. She started her career as a singer in the [[acid jazz]] band Crisp in the mid-1990s in [[Adelaide]]. In 1997, when Crisp disbanded, she released her debut [[studio album]], titled ''OnlySee'', in Australia. She moved to London and provided vocals for the British duo [[Zero 7]]. Sia released her second studio album, ''[[Healing Is Difficult]]'', in 2001, and her third, ''[[Colour the Small One]]'', in 2004.

Sia moved to New York City in 2005 and toured the United States. Her fourth and fifth studio albums, ''[[Some People Have Real Problems]]'' and ''[[We Are Born]]'', were released in 2008 and 2010, respectively. Each was certified gold by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] and attracted wider notice than her earlier albums. Uncomfortable with her growing fame, Sia took a hiatus from performing and focused on songwriting for other artists, producing successful collaborations "[[Titanium (song)|Titanium]]" (with [[David Guetta]]), "[[Diamonds (Rihanna song)|Diamonds]]" (with [[Rihanna]]) and "[[Wild Ones (song)|Wild Ones]]" (with [[Flo Rida]]).

In 2014, Sia broke through as a solo recording artist when her sixth studio album, ''[[1000 Forms of Fear]]'', debuted at No. 1 in the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and generated the top-ten single "[[Chandelier (song)|Chandelier]]" and a trilogy of music videos co-directed by Sia and starring child dancer [[Maddie Ziegler]]. Since then, Sia has usually worn a wig that obscures her face to protect her privacy.<ref name=Age/> Her seventh studio album, ''[[This Is Acting]]'' (2016), spawned her first [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] number one single, "[[Cheap Thrills (song)|Cheap Thrills]]". The same year, she began her [[Nostalgic for the Present Tour]], which incorporated dancing by Ziegler and others, and other performance art elements. Her eighth studio album, ''[[Everyday Is Christmas (album)|Everyday Is Christmas]]'', was released in 2017 and [[reissue]]d in 2018 with three bonus tracks. In 2018, she collaborated with [[Labrinth]] and [[Diplo]] in the group [[LSD (group)|LSD]], and they released their [[LSD (album)|self-titled debut album]] in April 2019. Sia has written many songs for films, and she directed a feature film, titled ''[[Music (2021 film)|Music]]'', which was released in early 2021 alongside an album, ''[[Music – Songs from and Inspired by the Motion Picture]]''.

She is an advocate for animal rights. Among the [[List of awards and nominations received by Sia|accolades]] received by Sia are nearly a dozen [[ARIA Awards]], 9 [[Grammy Award]] nominations and an [[MTV Video Music Award]].

==Early life and career==
Sia Kate Isobelle Furler was born on 18 December 1975 in [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]]. Her father, Phil Colson, is a musician, and her mother, Loene Furler, is an art lecturer.<ref name="Harry"/> Sia is the niece of actor-singer [[Kevin Colson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/theatre/kevin-colson-confesses-all-of-his-career-in-starry-firmament-20140926-10meub.html|title=Kevin Colson confesses all of his career in starry firmament|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|last=Craven|first=Peter|date=26 September 2014|access-date=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924162821/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/theatre/kevin-colson-confesses-all-of-his-career-in-starry-firmament-20140926-10meub.html|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Sia said that as a child she imitated the performing style of [[Aretha Franklin]], [[Stevie Wonder]] and [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], whom she cites as early influences.<ref name="NPR">{{cite interview|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=19075503|title=Sia Learns to Sound Like Herself|first=Alex|last=Cohen|author-link=Alex Cohen|publisher=[[NPR Music]]|date=15 February 2008|access-date=28 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228100728/https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=19075503|archive-date=28 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> She attended [[Adelaide High School]].<ref name="Harry">{{cite journal|url=http://www.mjmharry.com/docs/Sia-Furler.pdf| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101105010101/http://www.mjmharry.com/docs/Sia-Furler.pdf|title=Sia Sensation|first=Michael|last=Harry|journal=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Adelaide Advertiser]]|pages=24–26|archive-date=5 November 2010}}</ref> In the mid-1990s, Sia started a career as a singer in the local [[acid jazz]] band Crisp.<ref name="Harry"/> Sia collaborated with the band and contributed vocals to their album ''Word and the Deal'' (1996) and EP ''Delirium'' (1997).<ref>''Word and the Deal'' and ''Delirium'':
* {{cite web|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/15875159?selectedversion=NBD12798813|title=Word and the deal / Crisp. [sound recording]|publisher=[[National Library of Australia]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150114223832/http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/15875159?selectedversion=NBD12798813|archive-date=14 January 2015|url-status=dead}}
* {{cite web|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/24518036?q&versionId=29594043|title=Delirium / Crisp. [sound recording]|publisher=National Library of Australia|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115020959/http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/24518036?q&versionId=29594043|archive-date=15 January 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>
In 1997 Crisp disbanded,<ref name="SMHSia">{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-furler-fame-does-not-become-her-20100617-yjdr.html|title=Sia Furler: Fame does not become her|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|first=Andrew|date=18 June 2010|last=Murfett|access-date=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212030150/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-furler-fame-does-not-become-her-20100617-yjdr.html|archive-date=12 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and Sia released her debut [[studio album]], ''OnlySee'', on Flavoured Records, in Australia, on 23 December.<ref name="nloa">{{cite web| url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7556295?selectedversion=NBD13682423|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131225133718/http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7556295?selectedversion=NBD13682423| title=Onlysee / Sia Furler. [sound recording]|publisher=National Library of Australia|archive-date=25 December 2013}}</ref> The album sold about 1,200 copies.<ref name=savedherself/> Unlike her later albums, ''OnlySee'' was marketed under her full name, "Sia Furler". It was produced by Jesse Flavell.<ref>[https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7556295?selectedversion=NBD13682423 "Onlysee (sound recording) / Sia Furler"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108233421/https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7556295?selectedversion=NBD13682423 |date=8 January 2018 }}, Flavoured Records, 1997, Trove.nla.gov.au, accessed 8 January 2018</ref>

==Career==
===1997–2006: Zero 7, ''Healing Is Difficult'' and ''Colour the Small One''===
[[File:Sia Furler in concert.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Sia in concert in 2006]]
After Crisp disbanded in 1997, Sia moved to London,<ref name="SMHSia"/> where she performed as a background vocalist for British band [[Jamiroquai]].<ref name=AllMusic/> She also provided vocals for English downtempo group [[Zero 7]] on their first three studio albums and toured with the group.<ref name="Verrico"/> On Zero 7's 2001 album ''[[Simple Things (Zero 7 album)|Simple Things]]'', Sia contributed vocals to two tracks<ref name=allmusicsimple>{{cite web|title=Simple Things – Zero 7|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/simple-things-mw0000017246|website=AllMusic|access-date=19 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131201122541/http://www.allmusic.com/album/simple-things-mw0000017246|archive-date=1 December 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> including the single  "[[Destiny (Zero 7 song)|Destiny]]", which peaked at No. 30 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref name="SiaUK">{{cite web|url=http://officialcharts.com|title=Sia: Artist|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|access-date=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217061412/http://www.officialcharts.com/|archive-date=17 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2004, she provided vocals for Zero 7 on "[[Somersault (song)|Somersault]]" and "Speed Dial No. 2" (from the album ''[[When It Falls]]'').<ref name=allmusicwhen>{{cite web|last1=Bush|first1=John|title=When It Falls – Zero 7|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/when-it-falls-mw0000328826|website=AllMusic|access-date=19 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121205013320/http://www.allmusic.com/album/when-it-falls-mw0000328826|archive-date=5 December 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2006, Sia collaborated with Zero 7 for their third album, ''[[The Garden (Zero 7 album)|The Garden]]''.<ref name=allmusicgarden>{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=Marisa|title=The Garden – Zero 7|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-garden-mw0000542394|website=AllMusic|access-date=19 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326054553/http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-garden-mw0000542394|archive-date=26 March 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="BB09">{{cite magazine |last=Mason |first=Kerri |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EX4yD1pJCxUC&pg=PA56 |title=Albums: Zero 7 – Yeah Ghost |page=56 |magazine=Billboard |date=3 October 2009 |volume=121 |number=39 |access-date=21 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404070213/https://books.google.com/books?id=EX4yD1pJCxUC&pg=PA56 |archive-date=4 April 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 2000, Sia signed a recording contract with [[Sony Music]]'s sub-label Dance Pool and released her first [[single (music)|single]], "[[Taken for Granted]]", which peaked at No. 10 on the UK Singles Chart.<ref name=AllMusic/> In 2001, she released her second solo album, ''[[Healing Is Difficult]]'', which blends retro [[jazz]] and [[soul music]] and lyrically discusses Sia's dealing with the death of her first love affair.<ref name="SMHSia"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/healing-is-difficult-mw0000464188|title=Healing Is Difficult – Sia|website=AllMusic|first=Jon|last=O'Brien|access-date=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208212645/http://www.allmusic.com/album/healing-is-difficult-mw0000464188|archive-date=8 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Displeased with the promotion of the album, Sia fired her manager, left Sony Music and signed with [[Go! Beat Records|Go! Beat]], a subsidiary of [[Universal Music Group]] (UMG).<ref name="Verrico"/> At the [[APRA Awards of 2002]], Sia won the Breakthrough Songwriter category alongside Brisbane pop duo [[Aneiki]]'s Jennifer Waite and Grant Wallis.<ref name="APRAWin2002">{{cite web | url = http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/APRAAwards/MusicAwards/History/2002Winners.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110308004321/http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/APRAAwards/MusicAwards/History/2002Winners.aspx| title = 2002 Winners – APRA Music Awards | publisher = [[Australasian Performing Right Association]] | archive-date=8 March 2011 }}</ref>

In 2004, Sia released her third studio album, ''[[Colour the Small One]]''.<ref name="Ott">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/7735-colour-the-small-one/ |title=Sia – Colour the Small One |last1=Ott |first1=Chris |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=2 March 2004 |access-date=9 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816072120/http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/7735-colour-the-small-one/ |archive-date=16 August 2015 }}</ref> The album employs a mixture of [[acoustic music|acoustic instruments]] and [[electronic music|electronic]] backing to her material.<ref name="Ott"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/jan/02/popandrock.shopping|title=CD: Sia, Colour the Small One|work=[[The Guardian]]|first=Caroline|last=Sullivan|date=2 January 2004|access-date=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216150842/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/jan/02/popandrock.shopping|archive-date=16 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The album spawned four singles, including "[[Don't Bring Me Down (Sia song)|Don't Bring Me Down]]" and "[[Breathe Me]]", the latter of which charted in the United Kingdom,<ref name="SiaUK"/> Denmark and France.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://danishcharts.dk/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Breathe+Me&cat=s|title=Breathe Me – Sia|publisher=[[Tracklisten]]|language=da|access-date=16 February 2015}}</ref>

Dissatisfied with ''Colour the Small One''{{'}}s poor marketing and the album's struggle to connect with a mainstream audience, Sia relocated to New York City in 2005.<ref name="SMHSia"/> During that time, "Breathe Me" appeared in the final scene of the U.S. [[HBO]] television series ''[[Six Feet Under (TV series)|Six Feet Under]]'', which helped increase Sia's fame in the United States. Consequently, Sia's manager, David Enthoven, set up a tour across the country to maintain her career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html?_r=1|title=Sia Furler, the Socially Phobic Pop Star|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=20 April 2014|first=Steve|last=Knopper|access-date=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150214121101/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html?_r=1|archive-date=14 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>

===2007–2010: ''Some People Have Real Problems'' and ''We Are Born''===
[[File:Sia performing photograph by Kris Krug.jpg|thumb|right|Sia performing at [[South by Southwest]] in 2008]]
In 2007, Sia released a [[live album]], ''[[Lady Croissant]]'', which included eight live songs from her April 2006 performance at the [[Bowery Ballroom]] in New York and one new studio recording—"Pictures".<ref name="Brown">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/lady-croissant-mw0000557699|title=Sia – Lady Croissant|website=AllMusic|first=Marisa|last=Brown|access-date=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829134946/http://www.allmusic.com/album/lady-croissant-mw0000557699|archive-date=29 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> A year later, she left Zero 7 on friendly terms, replaced by [[ESKA|Eska Mtungwazi]] as the band's frontwoman.<ref name="BB09"/> Sia released her fourth studio album, ''[[Some People Have Real Problems]]'' on 8 January 2008. The album peaked at No. 41 in Australia and was [[List of music recording certifications|certified gold]] by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]].<ref name="Australia">Australian chart position and certification:
*{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Sia |title=Discography Sia |publisher=ARIA Charts |access-date=16 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227104853/http://www.australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Sia |archive-date=27 February 2015}}
*{{cite web|url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.aualbumaccreds2011.htm |title=Accreditations – 2011 Albums |publisher=Australian Recording Industry Association |access-date=16 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/64wvlBwg5?url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.auALBUMaccreds2011.htm |archive-date=25 January 2012}}</ref>
It charted at No. 26 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], becoming Sia's first to chart in the United States.<ref name="BB200">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/sia/chart?f=305|title=Sia – Chart history: Billboard 200|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214082755/http://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/Sia/chart?f=305|archive-date=14 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Some People Have Real Problems'' yielded four singles, including "[[The Girl You Lost to Cocaine]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nl-be.7digital.com/artist/sia/release/the-girl-you-lost-to-cocaine-3/|title=The Girl You Lost To Cocaine|publisher=[[7digital]]|location=Belgium|language=nl|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110073119/https://nl-be.7digital.com/artist/sia/release/the-girl-you-lost-to-cocaine-3/|archive-date=10 January 2015}}</ref> It peaked at No. 11 in the Netherlands and No. 12 in Spain;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=The+Girl+You+Lost+To+Cocaine&cat=s|title=Sia – The Girl You Lost to Cocaine|publisher=[[Single Top 100]]|access-date=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150113023803/http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=The+Girl+You+Lost+To+Cocaine&cat=s|archive-date=13 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> it additionally reached No. 8 on the US [[Hot Dance Club Songs]].<ref name="DanceClubSongs">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/sia/chart?f=359|title=Sia – Chart history: Dance Club Songs|magazine=Billboard|access-date=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620102739/http://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/Sia/chart?f=359|archive-date=20 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Another single from the album was "[[Soon We'll Be Found]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/soon-well-be-found-single/id705846139 |title=iTunes – Music – Soon We'll Be Found |publisher=iTunes Store |location=United Kingdom |archive-date=24 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224202640/https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/soon-well-be-found-single/id705846139 |url-status=dead}}</ref>

In May 2009, Sia released ''[[TV Is My Parent]]'' on [[DVD]], which includes a live concert at New York's Hiro Ballroom, four music videos and behind-the-scene footage.<ref name="MusicNews">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicnewsnet.com/2009/03/tv-is-my-parent-new-dvd-from-sia.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006160804/http://www.musicnewsnet.com/2009/03/tv-is-my-parent-new-dvd-from-sia.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=6 October 2011|title=TV is My Parent, New DVD from Sia|publisher=Music News Net|date=9 March 2009}}</ref> At the [[ARIA Music Awards of 2009]], Sia won the Best Music DVD category for ''TV Is My Parent''.<ref name="ARIAAward2009">{{cite web|url=http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php?year=2009 |title=ARIA Awards History|publisher=ARIA Awards|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100128034837/http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php|archive-date=28 January 2010}}</ref> She also received a nomination for Best Breakthrough Artist Album for ''Some People Have Real Problems''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Parker |first=Tappan |url=http://dailycollegian.com/2010/05/03/sia-brings-song-to-pearl-street/ |title=Sia brings song to Pearl Street |work=[[The Massachusetts Daily Collegian]] |date=3 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205015846/http://dailycollegian.com/2010/05/03/sia-brings-song-to-pearl-street/ |archive-date=5 December 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref>

In 2009, American singer [[Christina Aguilera]] approached Sia about writing [[ballad]]s for Aguilera's sixth studio album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/now-you-sia/story-e6frf7jo-1111119107653|title=Sia Furler is enjoying attentions of Christina Aguilera|work=[[Herald Sun]]|first=Cameron|last=Adams|date=12 March 2009|access-date=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140526164729/http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/now-you-sia/story-e6frf7jo-1111119107653|archive-date=26 May 2014|url-status=bot: unknown}}</ref> The final product, ''[[Bionic (Christina Aguilera album)|Bionic]]'', includes four songs co-written by Sia.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=[[Bionic (Christina Aguilera album)|Bionic]]|others=[[Christina Aguilera]]|year=2010|type=liner notes|publisher=[[RCA Records]], a division of [[Sony Music Entertainment]]}}</ref> Later in 2010, Sia also co-wrote "Bound to You" for [[Burlesque: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|the soundtrack]] of the film ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]'', which starred Aguilera and [[Cher]].<ref>{{cite magazine|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112044802/http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/magazine/reviews/albums/e3ibde532c77149bc3146237ecd8761e87d|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/magazine/reviews/albums/e3ibde532c77149bc3146237ecd8761e87d|title=Burlesque: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|magazine=Billboard|first=Kerri|last=Mason|date=11 December 2010|archive-date=12 January 2012}}</ref> The song was nominated for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] at the [[68th Golden Globe Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/ipad/jackie-weaver-nicole-kidman-geoffrey-rush-and-toni-collette-nominated-in-68th-golden-globe-awards/story-fn6bqphm-1225971265572|title=Jackie Weaver, Nicole Kidman, Geoffrey Rush and Toni Collette nominated in 68th Golden Globe Awards|work=The Adelaide Advertiser|date=15 December 2010|access-date=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120903005627/http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/ipad/jackie-weaver-nicole-kidman-geoffrey-rush-and-toni-collette-nominated-in-68th-golden-globe-awards/story-fn6bqphm-1225971265572|archive-date=3 September 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2011, Sia appeared on the [[The Voice (American season 1)|inaugural season]] of the U.S. version of ''[[The Voice (American TV series)|The Voice]]'' as an adviser for Aguilera, who served as a vocal coach and judge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2011/04/nbcs-the-voice-enlists-monica-reba-mcentire-sia-and-adam-blackstone-as-advisors.html|title=NBC's 'The Voice' enlists Monica, Reba McEntire, Sia and Adam Blackstone as advisors|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141104234733/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2011/04/nbcs-the-voice-enlists-monica-reba-mcentire-sia-and-adam-blackstone-as-advisors.html|date=29 April 2011|archive-date=4 November 2014}}</ref>

In June 2010, Sia released her fifth studio album, ''[[We Are Born]]''.<ref name="SiaWeAreBorn">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B003SP3WM2|title=We Are Born by Sia|publisher=Amazon.co.uk|access-date=16 February 2015}}</ref> The release peaked at No. 2 on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Albums Chart]] and was certified gold by the Australian Recording Industry Association.<ref name="Australia"/> The release of the album was preceded by three singles: the lead single, "[[You've Changed (Sia song)|You've Changed]]", was released in December 2009 and charted at No. 31 in Australia.<ref>"You've Changed" single release and chart position:
*{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/youve-changed-single/id348315733 |title=iTunes – Music – You've Changed |publisher=iTunes Store |location=New Zealand |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6WPE28MJO?url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/youve-changed-single/id348315733 |archive-date=17 February 2015 |url-status=dead }}
*{{cite web |url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=You%27ve+Changed&cat=s |title=You've Changed – Sia |publisher=ARIA Charts |access-date=17 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150201235222/http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=You%27ve+Changed&cat=s |archive-date=1 February 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> The follow-up single, "[[Clap Your Hands (Sia song)|Clap Your Hands]]", peaked at No. 17 in Australia, No. 10 in the Netherlands and No. 27 in Switzerland.<ref>
*{{cite web|url=http://www.bandit.fm/album/2688296?cc=AU|title=Clap Your Hands: Sia|publisher=bandit.fm|access-date=17 February 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217121806/http://www.bandit.fm/album/2688296?cc=AU|archive-date=17 February 2015}}
*{{cite web|url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Clap+Your+Hands&cat=s|title=Sia – Clap Your Hands|publisher=[[Single Top 100]]|access-date=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150321054914/http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Clap+Your+Hands&cat=s|archive-date=21 March 2015|url-status=live}}
</ref> At the [[ARIA Music Awards of 2010]], ''We Are Born'' earned Sia two categories won: Best Independent Release and Best Pop Release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history/year/2010|title=ARIA Awards History: 2010|publisher=ARIA Awards|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228203958/http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history/year/2010|archive-date=28 February 2014}}</ref> Meanwhile, at the 2011 [[APRA Awards (Australia)|APRA Music Awards]], Sia received a nomination for Song of the Year for "Clap Your Hands".<ref name="Collins">{{Cite news | url = http://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/entertainment/a/-/music/9653365/the-man-behind-the-songs/ | title = The Man Behind the Songs | last1 = Collins | first1 = Simon | work = [[The West Australian]]| date = 16 June 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120928111952/http://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/entertainment/a/-/music/9653365/the-man-behind-the-songs/|archive-date=28 September 2012 }}</ref> To promote ''We Are Born'', Sia gave the [[We Meaning You Tour]], which visited North America and Europe in April–May 2010.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2010/02/sia-announces-the-we-meaning-you-tour-dates|title=Sia Announces 'The We Meaning You Tour' Dates|magazine=[[Consequence of Sound]]|date=3 February 2010|first=Derek|last=Staples|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140831234421/http://consequenceofsound.net/2010/02/sia-announces-the-we-meaning-you-tour-dates/|archive-date=31 August 2014}}</ref> She followed this with the [[We Are Born Tour]], which visited Australia in February 2011 and North America in July–August 2011.<ref>We Are Born Tour:
*{{cite web|url=http://www.theaureview.com/the-goss/sia-announces-february-2011-australian-tour |title=Sia announces February 2011 Australian Tour |publisher=The AU Review |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140816133240/http://www.theaureview.com/the-goss/sia-announces-february-2011-australian-tour |archive-date=16 August 2014 |url-status=dead }}
*{{cite web|url=http://siamusic.net/tour |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715020744/http://siamusic.net/tour |title=Tour: Sia |publisher=Sia Music |archive-date=15 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

===2010–2013: Songwriting career and mainstream recognition===
[[File:Sia (5423995397) (Cropped).png|thumb|upright|right|Sia performing in 2011]]
Following the success of ''We Are Born'', Sia became uncomfortable with her growing fame. She later told ''[[The New York Times]]'': "I just wanted to have a private life. Once, as my friend was telling me they had cancer, someone came up and asked, in the middle of the conversation, if they could take a photograph with me. You get me? That's enough, right?"<ref name=Knopper>Knopper, Steve. [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html "Sia Furler, the Socially Phobic Pop Star"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170413151146/https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html |date=13 April 2017 }}, ''The New York Times'', 18 April 2014, accessed 26 October 2016</ref> She refused to do promos for her tours, began to wear a mask on stage and became increasingly dependent on drugs and alcohol on the road; she considered suicide.<ref name="Knopper" /> Sia fired Enthoven and hired Jonathan Daniel, who suggested that she write songs for other artists.<ref name=Knopper/>

Sia retired as a recording artist and began a career as a songwriter. She soon penned "[[Titanium (song)|Titanium]]" for American singer [[Alicia Keys]], but it was later sent to [[David Guetta]], who included Sia's original [[demo (music)|demo]] vocals on the song and released it as a single in 2011.<ref name="NPRMusic"/> "Titanium" peaked within the top ten of record charts in the United States, Australia and numerous European regions.<ref>Chart positions for "Titanium":
*{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=David+Guetta+feat.+Sia&titel=Titanium&cat=s|title=David Guetta feat. Sia – Titanium|publisher=ARIA Charts|access-date=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150201233616/http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=David+Guetta+feat%2E+Sia&titel=Titanium&cat=s|archive-date=1 February 2015|url-status=live}}
*{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/300445/David+Guetta/chart?f=379|title=David Guetta – Chart history: Hot 100|magazine=Billboard|access-date=18 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150614031257/http://www.billboard.com/artist/300445/David+Guetta/chart?f=379|archive-date=14 June 2015|url-status=live}}
</ref> However, Sia recalled: "I never even knew it was gonna happen, and I was really upset. Because I had just retired, I was trying to be a pop songwriter, not an artist."<ref name="NPRMusic">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2014/07/08/329500971/a-reluctant-star-sia-deals-with-fame-on-her-own-terms|title=A Reluctant Star, Sia Deals With Fame on Her Own|publisher=[[NPR Music]]| date=8 July 2014|first=Sam|last=Sanders|access-date=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150215153550/http://www.npr.org/2014/07/08/329500971/a-reluctant-star-sia-deals-with-fame-on-her-own-terms|archive-date=15 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>

From 2011 to 2013, Sia also co-wrote songs for many recording artists, including [[Beyoncé]], [[Kylie Minogue]], [[Flo Rida]] and [[Rihanna]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://6thfloor.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/21/how-a-song-written-by-sia-furler-becomes-a-hit/?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0|title=How a Song Written by Sia Furler Became a Hit|work=The New York Times|date=21 April 2014|first=Steve|last=Knopper|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205003032/http://6thfloor.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/21/how-a-song-written-by-sia-furler-becomes-a-hit/?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0|archive-date=5 December 2014}}</ref> Her collaboration with Flo Rida, "[[Wild Ones (song)|Wild Ones]]", peaked at No. 5 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and was the tenth best-selling song of 2012 globally.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ifpi.org/downloads/dmr2013-full-report_english.pdf | title=IFPI Digital Music Report 2013 | work=IFPI | access-date=3 October 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180529150621/http://www.ifpi.org/downloads/dmr2013-full-report_english.pdf | archive-date=29 May 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> In March 2012, Sia released a [[greatest hits album]], ''[[Best Of... (Sia album)|Best Of...]]'', in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.creammagazine.com/2012/03/hello-to-the-first-greatest-hits-set-from-sia/|title=Say hi to Sia's first greatest hits set|work=Cream|date=10 March 2012|access-date=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217132010/http://www.creammagazine.com/2012/03/hello-to-the-first-greatest-hits-set-from-sia| archive-date=17 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>

===2013–2014: Breakthrough with ''1000 Forms of Fear''===
In October 2013, Sia released "[[Elastic Heart]]" featuring [[The Weeknd]] and [[Diplo]] for [[The Hunger Games: Catching Fire – Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|the soundtrack]] of the American film ''[[The Hunger Games: Catching Fire]]'' (2013).<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055615/http://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases |url=http://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases |title=Top 40/R Future Releases |publisher=All Access Music Group |archive-date=21 September 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Sia executive-produced [[Brooke Candy]]'s debut EP, ''[[Opulence (EP)|Opulence]]'', released in May 2014, and co-wrote 3 songs on the EP.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.factmag.com/2014/04/28/brooke-candy-preps-debut-ep-does-sex-and-violence-in-opulence-video|title=Brooke Candy preps debut EP, does sex-and-violence in ''Opulence'' video|work=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]|date=28 April 2014|access-date=20 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320052522/http://www.factmag.com/2014/04/28/brooke-candy-preps-debut-ep-does-sex-and-violence-in-opulence-video/|archive-date=20 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In July 2014, Sia released her own sixth studio album, ''[[1000 Forms of Fear]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/1000-forms-of-fear-mw0002680594|title=1000 Forms of Fear – Sia|website=AllMusic|first=Heather|last=Phares|access-date=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210072510/http://www.allmusic.com/album/1000-forms-of-fear-mw0002680594|archive-date=10 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> She again collaborated with [[Greg Kurstin]].<ref name=KurstinCollab>
*{{cite magazine|last1=Leight|first1=Elias|title=Sia Announces New Christmas Album, Directorial Debut|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=1 August 2017|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sia-announces-new-christmas-album-directorial-debut-w495289|access-date=2 August 2017|publisher=Wenner Media LLC|issn=0035-791X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801205328/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sia-announces-new-christmas-album-directorial-debut-w495289|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}
*{{cite news|last1=McNeilage|first1=Ross|title=Sia Has Signed a New Record Deal and Is Releasing a Christmas Album|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/sia/news/sia-is-recording-a-christmas-album|access-date=2 August 2017|work=[[MTV News]]|publisher=[[MTV]]|date=1 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801210319/http://www.mtv.co.uk/sia/news/sia-is-recording-a-christmas-album|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The album debuted at No. 1 in the US ''Billboard'' 200 with first-week sales of 52,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/australia-culture-blog/2014/jul/17/sia-1000-forms-of-fear-no-1-us-album|title=Sia's 1000 Forms of Fear debuts at No 1 in US album charts|first=Clem|last=Bastow|date=17 July 2014|work=The Guardian|access-date=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217170434/http://www.theguardian.com/music/australia-culture-blog/2014/jul/17/sia-1000-forms-of-fear-no-1-us-album|archive-date=17 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> By October 2015, it was certified gold by the [[RIAA]] denoting 500,000 equivalent-album units sold in the United States.<ref>{{cite magazine|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151218061812/http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |archive-date= 18 December 2015 |url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |title=Upcoming Releases |magazine=Hits Daily Double |publisher=HITS Digital Ventures }}</ref> The record peaked at No. 1 in Australia and reached the top ten of charts in numerous European regions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=1000+Forms+Of+Fear&cat=a|title=Sia – 1000 Forms of Fear|publisher=ARIA Charts|access-date=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210000509/http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=1000+Forms+Of+Fear&cat=a|archive-date=10 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> It was certified silver by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] and gold by the Australian Recording Industry Association.<ref>"Chandelier" certifications:
*{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx |title=Certified Awards |format=''Enter the keyword "Sia" into the search parameter'' |publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]] |access-date=17 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6EEYfYVwc?url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx |archive-date=6 February 2013 }}
*{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140906185517/http://www.ariacharts.com.au/chart/albums |url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/chart/albums |title=ARIA Australian Top 50 Albums |publisher=ARIA Charts |archive-date=6 September 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref>
By early 2016, the album had sold 1 million copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-reclaims-the-songs-adele-rihanna-and-beyonce-rejected-to-rewrite-the-pop-blueprint/news-story/08460609cb95cfa5464a978b0682a215 | title=Sia reclaims the songs Adele, Rihanna and Beyonce rejected to rewrite the pop blueprint | work=News Corp Australia Network | date=29 January 2016 | access-date=1 October 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006120531/http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-reclaims-the-songs-adele-rihanna-and-beyonce-rejected-to-rewrite-the-pop-blueprint/news-story/08460609cb95cfa5464a978b0682a215 | archive-date=6 October 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref>

''1000 Forms of Fear''{{'}}s lead single, "[[Chandelier (song)|Chandelier]]" was released in March 2014. The song peaked at No. 8 on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100, becoming Sia's first entry on that chart as a lead artist.<ref name="Billboardhot100">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/Sia/chart?f=379|title=Sia – Chart history: Hot 100|magazine=Billboard|access-date=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150322040223/http://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/Sia/chart?f=379|archive-date=22 March 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Elsewhere, the song experienced similar commercial success, ranking in the top ten of the [[record chart]]s in Australia and numerous European regions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Chandelier&cat=s|title=Sia – Chandelier|publisher=ARIA Charts|access-date=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223151251/http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Chandelier&cat=s|archive-date=23 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> As of January 2015, the single had sold 2 million copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/music/nick-jonass-jealous-hits-a-new-peak-108110758051.html|title=Nick Jonas's 'Jealous' Hits a New Peak|first=Paul|last=Grein|publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]]|date=15 January 2015|access-date=15 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115011236/https://www.yahoo.com/music/nick-jonass-jealous-hits-a-new-peak-108110758051.html|archive-date=15 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> "[[Eye of the Needle (song)|Eye of the Needle]]" and "[[Big Girls Cry]]" were released as the second and third singles from the album, respectively, in June 2014.<ref>
*{{cite web |url=http://www.bandit.fm/album/7804041?cc=AU |title=Eye of the Needle |publisher=bandit.fm |access-date=17 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227052707/http://www.bandit.fm/album/7804041?cc=AU |archive-date=27 February 2015}}
*{{cite web |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6VQMICp5g?url=https://nl-be.7digital.com/artist/sia/release/big-girls-cry/ |url=https://nl-be.7digital.com/artist/sia/release/big-girls-cry |title=Big Girls Cry (2014) |publisher=7digital |location=Belgium |archive-date=8 January 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref>
In January 2015, Sia released a solo version of "[[Elastic Heart#Sia solo version|Elastic Heart]]" as the fourth single from ''1000 Forms of Fear''; it eventually reached the top 20 on the Hot 100.<ref name="ElasticHeart">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6443523/hot-100-chart-moves-sia-video-controversy|title=Hot 100 Chart Moves: Video Controversy Sends Sia's 'Elastic Heart' to No. 17 Debut|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=16 January 2015|magazine=Billboard|access-date=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120012212/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6443523/hot-100-chart-moves-sia-video-controversy|archive-date=20 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]] (2015), Sia received four nominations for "Chandelier": [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Solo Performance|Best Pop Solo Performance]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Music Video|Best Music Video]].<ref name=GrammyNoms2015>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/zackomalleygreenburg/2014/12/05/grammy-nominees-2015-the-full-list/|title=Grammy Nominees 2015: The Full List|first=Zack|last=O'Malley Greenburg|work=[[Forbes]]|date=5 December 2014|access-date=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205233150/http://www.forbes.com/sites/zackomalleygreenburg/2014/12/05/grammy-nominees-2015-the-full-list/|archive-date=5 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>

For performances of songs from ''1000 Forms of Fear'', Sia chose not to show her face, either facing away from audiences or hiding it behind oversized platinum blonde wigs. In videos for the singles "Chandelier", "Elastic Heart" and "Big Girls Cry", choreographed by [[Ryan Heffington]] and co-directed by Sia and [[Daniel Askill]], and in many of the promotional live performances, child dancer [[Maddie Ziegler]] performed as a proxy for Sia in bobbed blonde wigs similar to Sia's familiar hairstyle.<ref>Schumann, Rebecka. [http://www.ibtimes.com/dance-moms-star-maddie-ziegler-responds-snl-sia-chandelier-spoof-video-1713850 "''Dance Moms'' Star Maddie Ziegler Responds to ''SNL'' Sia 'Chandelier' Spoof"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226091440/http://www.ibtimes.com/dance-moms-star-maddie-ziegler-responds-snl-sia-chandelier-spoof-video-1713850 |date=26 February 2017 }}, ''International Business Times'', 27 October 2014, accessed 2 December 2015; Geslani, Michelle. [http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/12/sia-and-dance-prodigy-maddie-ziegler-deliver-gripping-performance-on-ellen-watch "Sia and dance prodigy Maddie Ziegler deliver gripping performance on Ellen – watch"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005142912/http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/12/sia-and-dance-prodigy-maddie-ziegler-deliver-gripping-performance-on-ellen-watch/ |date=5 October 2016 }}, ConsequenceofSound.net, 1 December 2015; Bailey, Alyssa. [http://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/news/a32257/sia-maddie-ziegler-ellen-degeneres-show "Watch Sia and Maddie Ziegler's Chilling Live Performance of 'Alive'"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610105719/http://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/news/a32257/sia-maddie-ziegler-ellen-degeneres-show/ |date=10 June 2016 }}, ''Elle'' magazine, 1 December 2015; and Swift, Andy. [http://tvline.com/2015/02/08/sia-kristen-wiig-grammy-performance-2015-grammys-chandelier "Sia Enlists Kristen Wiig for 'Chandelier' Performance at 2015 Grammy Awards"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160926150710/http://tvline.com/2015/02/08/sia-kristen-wiig-grammy-performance-2015-grammys-chandelier/ |date=26 September 2016 }}, Tvline.com, 8 February 2015</ref> The three videos have received a total of more than 4&nbsp;billion views on [[Vevo]].<ref>Furler, Sia. [https://www.youtube.com/user/SiaVEVO/videos?sort=p&view=0&flow=grid SiaVEVO: Most popular videos], YouTube, accessed 1 October 2022</ref> Sia explained to [[Kristen Wiig]] in an interview in ''[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]'' magazine that she decided to conceal her face to avoid a celebrity lifestyle and maintain some privacy: "I'm trying to have some control over my image. And I'm allowed to maintain some modicum of privacy. But also I would like not to be picked apart or for people to observe when I put on ten pounds or take off ten pounds or I have a hair extension out of place or my fake tan is botched. Most people don't have to be under that pressure, and I'd like to be one of them."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/music/sia|title=Sia|date=April 2015|work=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]|access-date=30 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529124817/http://www.interviewmagazine.com/music/sia/|archive-date=29 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The video for ''Elastic Heart'' "courted controversy and plaudits in equal measure", with some commentators perceiving it to have [[pedophilia|paedophilic]] undertones due to the relative ages of the dancers.<ref>Norton, Siobhan. [https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/features/ballet-fitness-why-growing-numbers-are-using-plis-and-pirouettes-to-work-out-10386434.html "Ballet fitness: Why growing numbers are using pliés and pirouettes to work out"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926034903/http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/features/ballet-fitness-why-growing-numbers-are-using-plis-and-pirouettes-to-work-out-10386434.html |date=26 September 2015 }}, ''The Independent'', 14 July 2015</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/jan/11/sia-video-pop-music-not-paedophilia?CMP=soc_567 "Sia's video: let's be wary of seeing paedophilia everywhere"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828233629/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/jan/11/sia-video-pop-music-not-paedophilia?CMP=soc_567 |date=28 August 2017 }}, ''[[Guardian Australia]]'', 11 January 2015</ref> Sia explained that the two dancers represented "warring 'Sia' self states", but she nevertheless apologised on Twitter to anyone who was "[[Trauma trigger|triggered]]".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://gma.yahoo.com/sia-apologizes-pedophilia-perception-music-video-133650931--abc-news-music.html |title=Sia Apologizes for 'Pedophilia' Perception in Music Video |publisher=Yahoo! |date=9 January 2015 |access-date=8 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110024135/https://gma.yahoo.com/sia-apologizes-pedophilia-perception-music-video-133650931--abc-news-music.html |archive-date=10 January 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=ElasticCont>Ranscombe, Siân. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopfeatures/11585580/The-10-most-controversial-music-videos.html "The 10 most controversial music videos"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180408070841/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopfeatures/11585580/The-10-most-controversial-music-videos.html |date=8 April 2018 }}, ''The Telegraph'', 10 May 2015</ref> Gia Kourlas wrote in ''The New York Times'' in 2016 that Sia's collaborations with Heffington have "done more to raise the standards of dance in pop music than nearly any current artist integrating the forms".<ref>Kourlas, Gia. [https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/24/arts/dance/for-sia-dance-is-where-the-human-and-the-weird-intersect.html?smid=tw-nytimesarts&smtyp=cur&_r=1 "For Sia, Dance Is Where the Human and the Weird Intersect"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813055653/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/24/arts/dance/for-sia-dance-is-where-the-human-and-the-weird-intersect.html?smid=tw-nytimesarts&smtyp=cur&_r=1 |date=13 August 2017 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]'', 19 July 2016, accessed 31 October 2016</ref> The "Chandelier" video was ranked as the 10th "greatest music video" of the 2010s by ''Billboard''.<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/list/8544596/best-music-videos-2010s-top-100 "The 100 Greatest Music Videos of the 2010s: Staff Picks"], ''Billboard'', 26 November 2019</ref>

In 2014, Sia contributed to the [[Annie (2014 film soundtrack)|soundtrack]] to the [[Annie (2014 film)|2014 film adaptation]] of the Broadway musical [[Annie (musical)|''Annie'']]. Sia, along with producer Greg Kurstin, wrote three new songs for the film as well as re-working songs from the musical.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rigby|first1=Sam|title=Sia and Beck Join Stars on Annie Movie Soundtrack|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a605383/sia-and-beck-join-stars-on-annie-movie-soundtrack.html#~oUASLyfKso2baF|website=[[Digital Spy]]|date=23 October 2014|publisher=Digital Spy|access-date=3 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141104005343/http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a605383/sia-and-beck-join-stars-on-annie-movie-soundtrack.html#~oUASLyfKso2baF|archive-date=4 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Sia, Kurstin and the film's director [[Will Gluck]] were nominated for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] at the [[72nd Golden Globe Awards]] for "Opportunity".<ref>{{cite web|last=Gray|first=Tim|date=15 December 2014|title='Birdman,' 'Grand Budapest' Top Critics Choice Awards Nominations|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/birdman-grand-budapest-pace-noms-for-critics-choice-awards-1201379383/|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216035611/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/birdman-grand-budapest-pace-noms-for-critics-choice-awards-1201379383/|archive-date=16 December 2014|access-date=15 December 2014|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>

===2015–2017: ''This Is Acting''===
[[File:SIaFurler Boston2016live.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Sia performing in 2016]]
In an interview with ''[[NME]]'' in February 2015, Sia revealed that she had completed the follow-up to ''1000 Forms of Fear'', entitled ''[[This Is Acting]]''. The album was another collaboration with producer and co-writer Greg Kurstin.<ref name=KurstinCollab/> Furler said that she released ''1000 Forms of Fear'' to free herself from her record deal and had planned simply to write for other artists, but the album's success spurred her to continue writing her own music.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/various-artists/82961|title=Sia reveals early details of brand new album ''This Is Acting''|date=17 February 2015|work=[[NME]]|access-date=19 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150218161220/http://www.nme.com/news/various-artists/82961|archive-date=18 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The same month, alongside the digital deluxe release of ''1000 Forms of Fear'', she released a mobile game, ''Bob Job''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McCown|first1=Alex|title=Sia releases a new game, still won't show herself|url=https://www.avclub.com/article/sia-releases-new-game-still-wont-show-herself-219026|access-date=18 September 2015|newspaper=A.V. Club|date=6 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913042827/http://www.avclub.com/article/sia-releases-new-game-still-wont-show-herself-219026|archive-date=13 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> "[[Alive (Sia song)|Alive]]" from ''This Is Acting'' was co-written by [[Adele]] and had originally been intended for Adele's third album.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Christina|title=Sia Details Next Single, Which Was Originally Written for Adele|url=http://www.idolator.com/7607168/sia-2015-album-this-is-acting-single-adele|website=Idolator|publisher=Time Inc.|date=7 September 2015|access-date=8 September 2015|archive-url=https://archive.today/20151105054010/http://www.idolator.com/7607168/sia-2015-album-this-is-acting-single-adele|archive-date=5 November 2015|url-status=bot: unknown}}</ref>

In November, Sia collaborated with composer [[J. Ralph]] on the soundtrack of the environmental documentary ''[[Racing Extinction]]'', co-writing and singing the song "One Candle".<ref>Spanos, Brittany. [https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-epic-new-song-one-candle-from-racing-extinction-trailer-20151105 "Hear Sia, J. Ralph's Epic New Song From ''Racing Extinction'' Trailer"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107031319/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-epic-new-song-one-candle-from-racing-extinction-trailer-20151105 |date=7 November 2017 }}, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', 5 November 2015. Retrieved 28 September 2016</ref> She also released two more songs from the album, "[[Bird Set Free]]"<ref>{{Citation|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KrT_0J6m6y8|access-date = 29 November 2015|title = Bird Set Free|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151126233141/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KrT_0J6m6y8|archive-date = 26 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and "One Million Bullets".<ref>{{Cite web|title = Sia Shares New Track "One Million Bullets"|url = https://pitchfork.com/news/62289-sia-shares-new-track-one-million-bullets|website = Pitchfork|date = 27 November 2015|access-date = 29 November 2015|language = en-US|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151130015805/http://pitchfork.com/news/62289-sia-shares-new-track-one-million-bullets/|archive-date = 30 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> "[[Cheap Thrills (song)|Cheap Thrills]]" and "[[Reaper (song)|Reaper]]" were subsequently released as promotional singles for the album. Eventually, the single "Cheap Thrills", featuring [[Sean Paul]], reached No. 1 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Trust|first1=Gary|title=Sia's 'Cheap Thrills' Takes No. 1 on Hot 100 From Drake|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7446766/sia-cheap-thrills-sean-paul-no-1-hot-100|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=25 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160726141731/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7446766/sia-cheap-thrills-sean-paul-no-1-hot-100|archive-date=26 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Sia released two videos for the song, one of which features Ziegler and two male dancers,<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7263981/sia-releases-captivating-cheap-thrills-video-featuring-maddie-ziegler "Sia Releases Captivating 'Cheap Thrills' Video Featuring Maddie Ziegler"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910215333/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7263981/sia-releases-captivating-cheap-thrills-video-featuring-maddie-ziegler |date=10 September 2016 }}, ''Billboard'', 21 March 2016; and Briones, Isis. [http://www.teenvogue.com/story/sia-maddie-ziegler-cheap-thrills-music-video "Sia's Music Video of New Single 'Cheap Thrills' With Maddie Ziegler Will Blow You Away"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918154550/http://www.teenvogue.com/story/sia-maddie-ziegler-cheap-thrills-music-video |date=18 September 2016 }}, ''Teen Vogue'', 21 March 2016</ref> while the other, featuring Sean Paul, shows a 1950s style teen dance party; it has accumulated more than 1.7 billion views.<ref>Sia. [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nYh-n7EOtMA "Sia – 'Cheap Thrills' (Lyric Video) ft. Sean Paul"], YouTube, 10 February 2016, accessed 10 December 2019</ref>

In April 2016, Sia gave a widely acclaimed performance at the [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]] that went [[viral video|viral]] online.<ref name="People Are Still Obsessed">{{Cite magazine|url=http://time.com/4299395/sia-coachella-performance/|title=People Are Still Obsessed With Sia's Incredible Coachella Performance|magazine=Time|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422051544/http://time.com/4299395/sia-coachella-performance/|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>
