</ref> The performance was her first full concert since 2011.<ref name="People Are Still Obsessed"/> In May 2016, Sia made a surprise appearance on the finale for ''[[Survivor: Kaôh Rōng]]'' where she donated $50,000 to contestant Tai Trang. She donated another $50,000 to an animal charity of his choice, noting that the two share a mutual love of animals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sia-gives-survivor-finalist-100k-for-being-an-animal-rights-activist_us_573d2480e4b0646cbeec23d9|title=Sia Gives 'Survivor' Finalist $100K For Being An Animal Rights Activist|website=The Huffington Post|date=18 May 2016|access-date=19 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160519041151/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sia-gives-survivor-finalist-100k-for-being-an-animal-rights-activist_us_573d2480e4b0646cbeec23d9|archive-date=19 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>

In June 2016, Sia gave a concert at [[Red Rocks Amphitheatre]] in Colorado, featuring Ziegler.<ref>Owens, Dylan. [http://www.heyreverb.com/blog/2016/06/23/welcome-sias-theater-dreams-red-rocks-seriesfest/118235/#16 "For SeriesFest, Sia welcomes Red Rocks to her theater of dreams"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924185311/http://www.heyreverb.com/blog/2016/06/23/welcome-sias-theater-dreams-red-rocks-seriesfest/118235/#16 |date=24 September 2016 }}, HeyReverb.com, ''[[The Denver Post]]'', 23 June 2016</ref> From May to August, Sia performed in nearly a dozen festival and other concerts in America and European and Middle Eastern countries, including Portugal, Denmark, Sweden, Finland, Hungary, Romania, Poland, the United Kingdom, Russia, Lebanon and Israel.<ref>Young, Alex. [http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/05/sia-announce-2016-world-tour-miguel-and-alunageorge-to-open ''Sia announce 2016 world tour, Miguel and AlunaGeorge to open''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002113531/http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/05/sia-announce-2016-world-tour-miguel-and-alunageorge-to-open/ |date=2 October 2016 }}, ''Consequence of Sound'', 16 May 2016, accessed 30 September 2016</ref><ref>[http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/sia-announces-tour-with-openers-miguel-and-alunageorge/11864459 ''Sia Announces Tour With Openers Miguel And AlunaGeorge''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002141105/http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/sia-announces-tour-with-openers-miguel-and-alunageorge/11864459 |date=2 October 2016 }}, ''[[Artistdirect|Artist Direct]]'', 17 May 2016, accessed 30 September 2016</ref><ref>Pate, Stephen. [http://njnnetwork.com/2016/08/sia-open-worldwide-tour-in-byblos-lebanon ''Sia Excites Crowd As Worldwide Tour Opens in Byblos Lebanon''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003091531/http://njnnetwork.com/2016/08/sia-open-worldwide-tour-in-byblos-lebanon/ |date=3 October 2016 }}, ''NJN Network'', 10 August 2016, accessed 30 September 2016</ref> In September 2016, she released a single, "[[The Greatest (Sia song)|The Greatest]]", with vocals from American hip hop recording artist [[Kendrick Lamar]]. A video was released the same day featuring Ziegler – the dancer's fifth video collaboration with Sia and Heffington.<ref name=GreatestGlicksman>Glicksman, Josh. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8478144/sia-maddie-ziegler-friendship-timeline "A Timeline of Sia & Maddie Ziegler's Friendship, From 'Chandelier' to a New Car"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004094825/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8478144/sia-maddie-ziegler-friendship-timeline |date=4 October 2018 }}, ''Billboard'', 3 October 2018; and Furler, Sia. [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GKSRyLdjsPA "Sia – The Greatest"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909002001/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GKSRyLdjsPA |date=9 September 2016 }}, SiaVEVO, 5 September 2016</ref> The two performed the song with several other dancers, and also performed "Chandelier", live the next day at the [[Apple Inc|Apple]] annual [[Apple media events|fall event]], drawing media attention.<ref>Moss, Rachel. [http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/maddie-ziegler-apple-launch-performance_uk_57d16502e4b0d45ff871392a "13-Year-Old Dancer Maddie Ziegler Totally Stole The Show At The Apple iPhone 7 Launch"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913015215/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/maddie-ziegler-apple-launch-performance_uk_57d16502e4b0d45ff871392a |date=13 September 2016 }}, ''Huffington Post'', 8 September 2016; and Robinson, Melia. [http://www.businessinsider.com/dancing-girl-apple-event-2016-9 "Meet the 13-year-old dancing sensation who stunned people at the big Apple event"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911144815/http://www.businessinsider.com/dancing-girl-apple-event-2016-9 |date=11 September 2016 }}, ''[[Business Insider]]'', 7 September 2016</ref> The videos that Sia has posted to her YouTube channel have accumulated a total of more than 12&nbsp;billion views,<ref>Furler, Sia. [https://www.youtube.com/c/sia/about Sia "About" page], YouTube, accessed 1 October 2022</ref> and the channel has more than 21 million subscribers.<ref>Furler, Sia. [https://www.youtube.com/user/siavideos/featured Sia], YouTube, accessed 1 October 2022</ref>

Sia gave her [[Nostalgic for the Present Tour]] in North America from September to November 2016, featuring Ziegler.<ref>Craddock, Lauren. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7446785/maddie-ziegler-sia-nostalgic-for-the-present-tour "Maddie Ziegler to Join Sia's Nostalgic for the Present Tour"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910061039/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7446785/maddie-ziegler-sia-nostalgic-for-the-present-tour |date=10 September 2016 }}, ''Billboard'', 25 July 2016</ref> As at Coachella and subsequent live performances, Sia appeared at the back of the stage with her familiar wig covering her face, while her dancers performed Heffington's choreography synchronised with pre-recorded videos played on big screens.<ref>Klein, Josh. [https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/ct-sia-miguel-review-ent-1018-20161017-story.html "Sia is a bundle of fascinating contradictions during United Center performance"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020045201/http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/ct-sia-miguel-review-ent-1018-20161017-story.html |date=20 October 2016 }}, ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', 17 October 2016</ref> The tour received a warm reaction: "She let her dancers own center stage, carrying out one skit/performance after another as Sia delivered the soundtrack. ... It defied all the regular rules of pop concerts, which are usually designed to focus every ounce of the audience's attention on the star of the show. Yet, Sia's bold gamble paid off, resulting in one of the most daringly original and wholly satisfying shows of 2016."<ref name="Harrington, Jim">{{cite web | url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2016/10/02/review-sia-rocks-with-kristen-wiig-paul-dano-in-oakland | title=Review: Sia delivers performance-art masterpiece in Oakland | work=The Mercury News | date=2 October 2016 | access-date=2 October 2016 | author=Harrington, Jim | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161004154408/http://www.mercurynews.com/2016/10/02/review-sia-rocks-with-kristen-wiig-paul-dano-in-oakland/ | archive-date=4 October 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> Ed Masley of ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'' described the show as "part performance art, part interpretive dance. ... [Sia] sounded amazing. ... There's so much raw emotion in her songs. And you can definitely hear that in her voice, but it becomes more visceral when you can also read it in the faces of her dancers, especially Ziegler. ... The entire performance was brilliantly staged, with one song flowing seamlessly into another".<ref>Masley, Ed. [https://www.azcentral.com/story/entertainment/music/2016/10/05/sia-concert-review-maddie-ziegler/91611028 "Review: Sia reinvented what it means to give a concert – part performance art, part Maddie Ziegler"], ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'', 5 October 2016</ref> Sia released the deluxe edition of ''This Is Acting'' in October 2016, which includes three new tracks, a remix version of "Move Your Body" and a solo version of "The Greatest".<ref>Raynor, Madeline. [https://www.ew.com/article/2016/10/21/sia-this-acting-deluxe-new-songs "Sia releases 3 new tracks on ''This is Acting'' deluxe version"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161023035131/http://www.ew.com/article/2016/10/21/sia-this-acting-deluxe-new-songs |date=23 October 2016 }}, ''Entertainment Weekly'', 21 October 2016</ref> She was nominated for three 2017 Grammy Awards.<ref name=GrammyNoms2017>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7597556/grammys-nominees-complete-list-2017 "Here Is the Complete List of Nominees for the 2017 Grammys"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206151125/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7597556/grammys-nominees-complete-list-2017 |date=6 December 2016 }}, ''Billboard'' magazine, 6 December 2016</ref> Sia co-wrote and performed on a platinum-selling single, "[[Dusk Till Dawn (Zayn song)|Dusk Till Dawn]]", by [[Zayn Malik|Zayn]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Leight|first=Elias|title=Watch Jemima Kirke in Noir Thriller For Zayn Malik, Sia's New Song|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=7 September 2017|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/see-zayn-malik-in-noir-thriller-dusk-till-dawn-video-w501630|access-date=20 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920141652/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/see-zayn-malik-in-noir-thriller-dusk-till-dawn-video-w501630|archive-date=20 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=ZAYN&ti=DUSK+TILL+DAWN+%28FEAT.+SIA%29 "Zayn: 'Dusk Till Dawn' (Feat. Sia)"], RIAA, accessed 24 October 2018</ref>

Sia performed in concert at the close of the [[Dubai World Cup]] in March 2017, together with her dancers, led by Ziegler.<ref>Hamad, Marwa. [http://gulfnews.com/life-style/music/sia-dons-her-wig-during-theatrical-dubai-gig-1.2000413 "Sia dons her wig during theatrical Dubai gig"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326223344/http://gulfnews.com/life-style/music/sia-dons-her-wig-during-theatrical-dubai-gig-1.2000413 |date=26 March 2017 }}, ''Gulf News'', 26 March 2017</ref> They gave a second leg of the Nostalgic for the Present Tour, her first stadium tour in Australasia, in late 2017.<ref>
*{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7809643/sia-stadium-tour-australia-new-zealand |title=Sia Plots First Stadium Tour of Australia and New Zealand |last=Brandle |first=Lars |date=29 May 2017 |magazine=Billboard |access-date=29 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170529081115/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7809643/sia-stadium-tour-australia-new-zealand |archive-date=29 May 2017 |url-status=live }}
*He, Richard S. [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/dec/01/sia-review-when-she-transcends-spectacle-she-soars "Sia review – when she transcends spectacle, she soars"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180101172948/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/dec/01/sia-review-when-she-transcends-spectacle-she-soars |date=1 January 2018 }}, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 30 November 2017, accessed 28 January 2018
</ref>

===2017–present: ''Everyday Is Christmas'', ''LSD'' and ''Music''===
In 2017, Sia moved from RCA to [[Atlantic Records]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7882275/sia-christmas-album-atlantic-records-deal|title=Sia Signs to Atlantic Records, Announces Christmas Album|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|date=1 August 2017|access-date=1 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801183635/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7882275/sia-christmas-album-atlantic-records-deal|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> She released the album ''[[Everyday Is Christmas (album)|Everyday Is Christmas]]'' on Atlantic and Monkey Puzzle in November 2017. The album features original songs co-written and co-produced with Kurstin.<ref>
*{{cite magazine|last1=Kaufman|first1=Gil|title=Sia Signs to Atlantic Records, Announces Christmas Album|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=1 August 2017|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7882275/sia-christmas-album-atlantic-records-deal|access-date=2 August 2017|issn=0006-2510|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801194617/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7882275/sia-christmas-album-atlantic-records-deal|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}
*{{cite journal|title=Sia Signs with Atlantic Records, Christmas Album Due This Year|journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=1 August 2017|url=https://variety.com/2017/music/news/sia-signs-with-atlantic-records-christmas-album-due-this-year-1202512120/|access-date=2 August 2017|issn=0042-2738|oclc=810134503|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801173836/http://variety.com/2017/music/news/sia-signs-with-atlantic-records-christmas-album-due-this-year-1202512120/|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}
</ref> She promoted it by releasing the single "[[Santa's Coming for Us]]" and the track "Snowman",<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-joyous-seasonal-song-santas-coming-for-us-w510478|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=16 April 2018|title=Hear Sia's Joyous Seasonal Song 'Santa's Coming for Us|author=Daniel Kreps|date=30 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180417105614/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-joyous-seasonal-song-santas-coming-for-us-w510478|archive-date=17 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8031327/sia-new-song-snowman-christmas-album-listen|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=16 April 2018|title=Sia Shares New Song, Snowman, Says She Wrote Christmas Album By Accident|date=11 November 2017|author=Mary J. DiMeglio|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424042351/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8031327/sia-new-song-snowman-christmas-album-listen|archive-date=24 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> which she performed during the finale of the [[The Voice (American season 13)|13th season of ''The Voice'']] and on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'' together with Maddie Ziegler.<ref>Aniftos, Rania. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8070501/sia-maddie-ziegler-reunite-perform-snowman-ellen "Sia & Maddie Ziegler Reunite to Perform 'Snowman' on ''Ellen'': Watch"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180105220316/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8070501/sia-maddie-ziegler-reunite-perform-snowman-ellen |date=5 January 2018 }}, ''Billboard'', 13 December 2017</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/tv/news/e2-80-98the-voice-e2-80-99-finale-recap-the-winner-of-season-13-is-revealed/ar-BBH31du|publisher=[[MSN]]|access-date=16 April 2018|title=The Voice Finale Recap: The Winner Of Season 13 Is Revealed|author=Alyssa Norwin|date=20 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418031517/https://www.msn.com/en-us/tv/news/e2-80-98the-voice-e2-80-99-finale-recap-the-winner-of-season-13-is-revealed/ar-BBH31du|archive-date=18 April 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> In November 2018, Sia released the deluxe edition of the album, containing three bonus tracks, as a [[Target Corporation|Target]] exclusive.<ref>Lenniger, Shea. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8482991/sia-deluxe-christmas-album-stream "Sia Releases Deluxe Version of Her Christmas Album: Listen"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103123309/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8482991/sia-deluxe-christmas-album-stream |date=3 November 2018 }}, ''Billboard'', 2 November 2018</ref>

In 2018, Sia collaborated with English musician [[Labrinth]] and American DJ/record producer [[Diplo]], under the name [[LSD (group)|LSD]], to release four songs,<ref>[https://variety.com/2018/music/news/lsd-sia-diplo-and-labrinth-team-up-for-new-song-genius-listen-1202796730 "Sia, Diplo and Labrinth Team Up for New Song 'Genius' (Listen)"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616065328/https://variety.com/2018/music/news/lsd-sia-diplo-and-labrinth-team-up-for-new-song-genius-listen-1202796730/ |date=16 June 2018}}, ''Variety'', 3 May 2018; Rettig, James. [https://www.stereogum.com/1995583/lsd-sia-diplo-labrinth-audio-video/video "LSD (Sia, Diplo, & Labrinth) – 'Audio' Video"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616153713/https://www.stereogum.com/1995583/lsd-sia-diplo-labrinth-audio-video/video/ |date=16 June 2018 }}, [[Stereogum]], 10 May 2018; and Bein, Kat. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8482791/lsd-mountains-new-song "LSD Reaches New Heights on 'Mountains'"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181102165506/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8482791/lsd-mountains-new-song |date=2 November 2018 }}, ''Billboard'', 1 November 2018</ref> which were then released as an EP called ''Mountains'' on Spotify.<ref name="Legaspi">{{cite magazine |last1=Legaspi |first1=Althea |title=Hear Diplo, Sia, Labrinth Move 'Mountains' on New Song |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=1 November 2018 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/diplo-sia-labrinth-mountains-new-lsd-song-750952/ |access-date=3 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181102175747/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/diplo-sia-labrinth-mountains-new-lsd-song-750952/ |archive-date=2 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The group released an album, ''[[LSD (album)|Labrinth, Sia & Diplo Present... LSD]]'', in April 2019,<ref>Daw, Stephen. (11 March 2019). [https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8501893/diplo-sia-labrinth-announce-debut-lsd-album-release-date "Diplo, Sia & Labrinth Announce Debut LSD Album Release Date"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190315104320/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8501893/diplo-sia-labrinth-announce-debut-lsd-album-release-date |date=15 March 2019 }}, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. Retrieved 11 March 2019</ref> containing the same four songs, five new songs and a previously released remix of their track "[[Genius (LSD song)|Genius]]" with [[Lil Wayne]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/labrinth-sia-diplo-present-lsd/1455271201|title=Labrinth, Sia & Diplo Present... LSD by LSD on iTunes|website=iTunes Store|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328164726/https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/labrinth-sia-diplo-present-lsd/1455271201|archive-date=28 March 2019|url-status=live|access-date=12 April 2019}}</ref> Also in 2018, Sia was one of the narrators of Australian animal rights documentary ''[[Dominion (documentary)|Dominion]]'',<ref>Webber, Jemima. [https://www.livekindly.co/vegan-celebrity-sia-joins-cast-of-new-animal-rights-documentary-dominion "Vegan Celebrity Sia Joins Cast of New Animal Rights Documentary Dominion"], LiveKindly.co, 18 May 2018, accessed 14 February 2020</ref> and shared in a 2018 Award of Excellence from the Hollywood International Independent Documentary Awards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hiida.com/july-2018-winners.html|title=July 2018 Winners|website=Hollywood International Independent Documentary Awards}}</ref>

Sia's ninth album, ''[[Music – Songs from and Inspired by the Motion Picture]]'', was released in February 2021 in connection with the release of her film, ''[[Music (2021 film)|Music]]''.<ref>{{Cite web| last=Aswad|first=Jem|date=2020-11-19|title=Sia Drops 'Hey Boy', First Song From Her Directorial Debut Film, 'Music'|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/sia-drops-hey-boy-directorial-debut-film-music-1234835837/|access-date=2021-02-06|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref> She is reportedly working on her tenth album, to be titled ''Reasonable Woman''.<ref>{{Cite web| last=Mahjouri| first=Shakiel| date=12 November 2020|title=Sia Teases New Song 'Hey Boy' With Help From Maddie Ziegler and Instagram Reels|url=https://etcanada.com/news/713036/sia-teases-new-song-hey-boy-with-help-from-maddie-ziegler-and-instagram-reels|website=ET Canada}}</ref>

==Artistry and musical style==
At the start of her career, with the bands Crisp<ref name=AllmusicHealing>{{cite web|last1=O'Brien|first1=Jon|title=Sia: Healing is Difficult|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/healing-is-difficult-mw0000464188|website=AllMusic|access-date=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717024024/https://www.allmusic.com/album/healing-is-difficult-mw0000464188|archive-date=17 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Jamiroquai]], Sia performed [[acid jazz]] in Australia and later in London.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Prato|first1=Greg|title=Jamiroquai Overview|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/jamiroquai-mn0000176358|website=AllMusic|access-date=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201041752/https://www.allmusic.com/artist/jamiroquai-mn0000176358|archive-date=1 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> With her first solo single, "Taken for Granted", she experimented with [[trip hop]].<ref name=AllmusicHealing/> When she joined Zero 7, she sang [[downtempo]] numbers.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wesolowski|first1=David Peter|title=Zero 7 Overview|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/zero-7-mn0000696668|website=AllMusic|access-date=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413190527/https://www.allmusic.com/artist/zero-7-mn0000696668|archive-date=13 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>

With ''[[Colour the Small One]]'' (2004) and ''[[Some People Have Real Problems]]'' (2007) she moved into [[jazz]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sullivan|first1=Caroline|title=Sia, Colour the Small One|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/jan/02/popandrock.shopping|access-date=13 April 2018|work=The Guardian|date=1 January 2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180718180149/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/jan/02/popandrock.shopping|archive-date=18 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[folktronica]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=O'Brien|first1=Jon|title=Sia: Colour the Small One|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/colour-the-small-one-mw0000463309|website=AllMusic|access-date=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104214544/https://www.allmusic.com/album/colour-the-small-one-mw0000463309|archive-date=4 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> although the album's biggest hit, "[[Breathe Me]]", is described as [[alternative rock]] and a [[power ballad]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sia: Breathe Me|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/breathe-me-mw0001977876|website=AllMusic|access-date=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201044614/https://www.allmusic.com/album/breathe-me-mw0001977876|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Some People Have Real Problems'' expanded her connection with [[indie pop]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mason|first1=Stewart|title=Some People Have Real Problems|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/some-people-have-real-problems-mw0000492954|website=AllMusic|access-date=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201131351/https://www.allmusic.com/album/some-people-have-real-problems-mw0000492954|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Some People Have Real Problems / Sia| url=https://www.billboard.com/bbcom/content_display/reviews/albums/e3i5d4ee6c1f9636327deaa5402a021aa97| magazine=Billboard|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080925190851/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/content_display/reviews/albums/e3i5d4ee6c1f9636327deaa5402a021aa97|archive-date=25 September 2008}}</ref> Sia stated, "''Colour the Small One'' ... couldn't be more derivative of [[Kings of Convenience]] and [[James Taylor]] and the things that Zero 7 were playing on the [tour] bus. I'm very easily influenced."<ref name="Rolling Stone">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/sias-reject-opus-songwriter-on-reclaiming-adele-rihannas-unwanted-hits-20151203?page=4|title=Sia on Reclaiming Adele, Rihanna's Unwanted Hits|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=3 December 2015|access-date=11 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913213312/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/sias-reject-opus-songwriter-on-reclaiming-adele-rihannas-unwanted-hits-20151203?page=4|archive-date=13 September 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>

In 2009, after leaving Zero 7, Sia dedicated herself entirely to her solo career.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Leahey|first1=Andrew|title=Sia Biography|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/sia-mn0000753742/biography|website=AllMusic|access-date=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717014836/https://www.allmusic.com/artist/sia-mn0000753742/biography|archive-date=17 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[We Are Born]]'' (2010), incorporated various pop styles, including [[synthpop]] and [[R&B]], with introspective themes accompanied by more insistent and livelier rhythms.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hoffman|first1=K. Ross|title=Sia: We Are Born|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/we-are-born-mw0001988460|website=AllMusic|access-date=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413190530/https://www.allmusic.com/album/we-are-born-mw0001988460|archive-date=13 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''1000 Forms of Fear'' (2014) consolidated her connection with pop (with traces of [[electropop]], reggae and hip-hop),<ref>{{cite web |last=Zaleski |first=Marah |url=https://www.avclub.com/review/accidental-pop-songwriter-sia-doesnt-quite-reclaim-206353 |title=Accidental pop songwriter Sia doesn't quite reclaim solo career momentum |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=8 July 2014 |access-date=8 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140712061920/http://www.avclub.com/review/accidental-pop-songwriter-sia-doesnt-quite-reclaim-206353 |archive-date=12 July 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fares|first1=Heather|title=Sia: 1000 Forms of Fear|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/1000-forms-of-fear-mw0002680594|website=AllMusic|access-date=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627144311/https://www.allmusic.com/album/1000-forms-of-fear-mw0002680594|archive-date=27 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> while ''This Is Acting'' (2016) is mostly composed of songs written by Sia with other female pop artists in mind, but the artists did not include the songs on their albums.<ref name="guardian">{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jan/31/sia-this-is-acting-review-favourite-rejects-beyonce-rihanna-adele | title=Sia: This Is Acting review – mass-appeal pop with a manic edge | work=The Guardian | date=31 January 2016 | access-date=2 October 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003154023/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jan/31/sia-this-is-acting-review-favourite-rejects-beyonce-rihanna-adele | archive-date=3 October 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> Sia described songwriting for others as "play-acting."<ref name="Rolling Stone"/> ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s Kitty Empire commented that the latter album "provides an obvious counterpoint to Sia's more personal album of 2014, ''1000 Forms of Fear'', whose stonking single, "Chandelier", tackled her intoxicated past. ''This Is Acting'' makes plain the fact of manufacture – a process akin to bespoke tailoring."<ref name="guardian"/> The record also alternates reggae and electropop with more introspective themes.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chau|first1=Thomas|date=7 September 2015|title=Sia Reveals that She Originally Wrote Her Next Single for Adele|url=http://popcrush.com/sia-new-single-alive-adele/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909205054/http://popcrush.com/sia-new-single-alive-adele/|archive-date=9 September 2015|access-date=13 April 2018|website=Popcrush}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Phares|first1=Heather|title=Sia: This Is Acting|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/this-is-acting-mw0002894912|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709011409/https://www.allmusic.com/album/this-is-acting-mw0002894912|archive-date=9 July 2018|access-date=13 April 2018|website=AllMusic}}</ref>

In her 2016 live performances, Sia's music was part of performance-art-like shows that involved dance and theatrical effects.<ref name="Harrington, Jim"/><ref name="seattle times">{{cite web | url=http://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/music/hitmaker-sia-kicks-off-nostalgia-for-the-present-tour-at-keyarena | title=Hitmaker Sia begins 'Nostalgic for the Present' tour at the Key | work=Seattle Times | date=1 October 2016 | access-date=1 October 2016 | author=De Barros, Paul | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925170836/http://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/music/hitmaker-sia-kicks-off-nostalgia-for-the-present-tour-at-keyarena/ | archive-date=25 September 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> An [[MTV News]] writer opined that "Sia's throaty, slurred vocals are her norm",<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2741713/rihanna-adele-and-what-happens-when-female-voices-show-their-pain/ | title=Rihanna, Adele, and What Happens When Female Voices Show Their Pain | work=MTV News | date=18 February 2016 | access-date=2 October 2016 | author=Cills, Hazel | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003194908/http://www.mtv.com/news/2741713/rihanna-adele-and-what-happens-when-female-voices-show-their-pain/ | archive-date=3 October 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> while a contributor to ''[[The Fader]]'' noted that "in the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 landscape, Sia's songwriting voice, which deals with depression and addiction, is singular—her actual voice even more so."<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thefader.com/2016/01/21/sia-voice-this-is-acting-rihanna-beyonce | title=How Sia's Polarising Vocals Have Invaded The Pop Mainstream | work=The Fader | date=21 January 2016 | access-date=2 October 2016 | author=Cliff, Aimee | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921170921/http://www.thefader.com/2016/01/21/sia-voice-this-is-acting-rihanna-beyonce | archive-date=21 September 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''Everyday Is Christmas'' (2017), Sia's first release of [[Christmas music]], is a pop album that gives old-fashioned holiday music "some 21st century pop gloss"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Phares|first1=Heather|title=Sia: Everyday Is Christmas|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/everyday-is-christmas-mw0003118444|website=AllMusic|access-date=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717013042/https://www.allmusic.com/album/everyday-is-christmas-mw0003118444|archive-date=17 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and is made for those who grow tired of the classics.<ref>{{cite web|date=17 November 2017|title=Sia has created a holiday album for those who don't love classics|url=https://abcnews.go.com/amp/Entertainment/sia-created-holiday-album-love-classics/story?id=51234151|access-date=6 April 2021|work=[[ABC News]]}}</ref> ''Music – Songs from and Inspired by the Motion Picture'' (2021) further developed Sia's pop music catalogue, with the album incorporating more electropop and reggae, alongside [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] and EDM.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Richardson|first=Mark|date=10 February 2021|title='Music' by Sia Review: Stuck in the Now|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/music-by-sia-review-stuck-in-the-now-11612993256|url-status=live|url-access=subscription|access-date=6 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210211113740/https://www.wsj.com/articles/music-by-sia-review-stuck-in-the-now-11612993256|archive-date=11 February 2021}}</ref> [[NPR|National Public Radio]] called Sia "the 21st century's most resilient songwriter".<ref>St. Asaph, Katherine. [https://wamu.org/story/18/11/06/sia-is-the-21st-centurys-most-resilient-songwriter "Sia Is The 21st Century's Most Resilient Songwriter"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107145333/https://wamu.org/story/18/11/06/sia-is-the-21st-centurys-most-resilient-songwriter/|date=7 November 2018}}, NPR, 6 November 2018</ref>

==Accolades and recognition==
{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Sia}}
Sia has received an array of accolades, including [[ARIA Awards]], an [[MTV Video Music Award]] and nine nominations for [[Grammy Award]]s.<ref name=GrammyNoms2015/><ref name=GrammyNoms2017/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2012/12/05/grammy-nominees-list/1749735|title=55th annual Grammy Awards nominees|work=[[USA Today]]|access-date=17 March 2014|date=16 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140314035249/http://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2012/12/05/grammy-nominees-list/1749735/|archive-date=14 March 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>
{{Cite web |url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/sia |title=GRAMMY Awards Results for Sia |work=Grammy.com |access-date=28 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117112351/https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/sia |archive-date=17 November 2017 |url-status=live }}
</ref>

In March 2021, a [[alley|laneway]] in [[Adelaide city centre]] was renamed Sia Furler Lane, and a mural titled ''She Imagined Buttons'' was painted on a wall nearby to commemorate Sia's 2011 performance in Adelaide.<ref>{{cite web | last=Gallagher | first=Alex | title=Laneway honouring Sia officially launched in Adelaide | website=NME | date=24 March 2021 | url=https://www.nme.com/en_au/news/music/sia-furler-lane-adelaide-unveiled-2906823 | access-date=5 August 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last=Brandle | first=Lars | title=Adelaide launches Sia Furler Lane, first of its music laneways | website=The Music Network | date=23 March 2021 | url=https://themusicnetwork.com/sia-furler-lane-adelaide/ | access-date=5 August 2022}}</ref> As of October 2022, Sia has 15&nbsp;entries on the [[APRA billion streams list]], the most of any artist.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.apraamcos.com.au/about/supporting-the-industry/awards/the-1-000-000-000-list |title=The 1,000,000,000 list |publisher=APRA AMCOS |access-date=1 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221001072024/https://www.apraamcos.com.au/about/supporting-the-industry/awards/the-1-000-000-000-list |archive-date=1 October 2022 |url-status=live}} Note: Non-Australasian co-writers are not shown.</ref>

==Other ventures==
In the 2014 ''[[South Park]]'' episode "[[The Cissy]]", Sia provided the vocals for the fictional [[Lorde]] track "Push (Feeling Good on a Wednesday)".<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Kaye |first1=Ben|title=''South Park'' releases full version of Lorde spoofing "Push (Feel Good on a Wednesday)" – listen |url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2014/10/south-park-releases-full-version-of-lorde-spoofing-push-feel-good-on-a-wednesday-listen| access-date=18 September 2015|magazine=Consequence of Sound|date=16 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927093640/http://consequenceofsound.net/2014/10/south-park-releases-full-version-of-lorde-spoofing-push-feel-good-on-a-wednesday-listen| archive-date=27 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2016 Sia covered "[[Blackbird (Beatles song)|Blackbird]]" by [[The Beatles]] for the [[Netflix]] original series ''[[Beat Bugs]]''.<ref name="blackbirdsia">{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sia-pink-beat-bugs-beatles-covers_us_57a0d767e4b0693164c2db69|title=Listen To Sia And Pink Cover The Beatles For Netflix's Adorable 'Beat Bugs'|first=Julia|last=Brucculieri|date=2 August 2016|access-date=11 March 2017|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312064411/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sia-pink-beat-bugs-beatles-covers_us_57a0d767e4b0693164c2db69|archive-date=12 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> She appeared in the 2017 animated film ''[[My Little Pony: The Movie (2017 film)|My Little Pony: The Movie]]'' as the voice of pop star Songbird Serenade. She also contributed an original song, "[[Rainbow (Sia song)|Rainbow]]", to [[My Little Pony: The Movie (soundtrack)|the film's soundtrack]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/comic-con-sia-joins-my-little-pony-movie-1201820722/|title=Sia Joins the Voice Cast of 'My Little Pony: The Movie'|work=Variety|date=22 July 2016|access-date=22 July 2016|first=Dave|last=McNary|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160723163849/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/comic-con-sia-joins-my-little-pony-movie-1201820722/|archive-date=23 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Sia wrote the songs for the [[Vox Lux (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] to the 2018 musical film ''[[Vox Lux]]'', with a score by [[Scott Walker (singer)|Scott Walker]].<ref name=Barfield>{{cite web| url=https://theplaylist.net/sia-scott-walker-vox-lux-20180821| title=Sia & Scott Walker Providing The Music For Natalie Portman Musical Drama ''Vox Lux''| last=Barfield| first=Charles| date=21 August 2018| access-date=23 August 2018| work=The Playlist| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823210559/https://theplaylist.net/sia-scott-walker-vox-lux-20180821| archive-date=23 August 2018| url-status=live}}</ref>

She wrote a screenplay, based on a story that she had written in 2007,<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Anderson|first1=Ariston|title=Venice: Sia Explains Why She's Directing Her Maddie Ziegler Screenplay|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/venice-sia-says-film-starring-820853|access-date=18 September 2015|magazine=The Hollywood Reporter|date=7 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150911054358/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/venice-sia-says-film-starring-820853|archive-date=11 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> for the 2021 musical film, ''[[Music (2021 film)|Music]]'', which starred Ziegler, [[Kate Hudson]] and [[Leslie Odom Jr.]]<ref name=savedherself>{{Cite magazine| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/sia-face-songs-chandelier-maddie-ziegler-712691/|title=How Sia Saved Herself|last=Aron|first=Hillel|date=24 August 2018|magazine=Rolling Stone|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref> Sia also directed the film and wrote its soundtrack.<ref>Nolfi, Joey. [https://ew.com/movies/music-trailer-kate-hudson-sia "Kate Hudson makes sweet Music in Sia's directorial debut trailer"], ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', November 19, 2020</ref> The film was released in Australia in January 2021 and in select [[IMAX]] theatres in the US for one night on 10 February 2021, followed by an on-demand release. It received negative reviews from critics<ref name=":4">{{Cite web| last=Breihan| first=Tom| date=11 February 2021| title=Critics Hate Sia's Directorial Debut 'Music'|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2116045/critics-hate-music/news/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210214030226/https://www.stereogum.com/2116045/critics-hate-music/news/|archive-date=2021-02-14|access-date=2021-02-26|website=[[Stereogum]]}}</ref><ref name="RT">{{Cite web|title=''Music'' (2021)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/music|access-date=April 24, 2021|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]}}</ref> and generated controversy for its depiction of autism. It was nominated for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture – Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture – Musical or Comedy]] at the [[78th Golden Globe Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Darville|first=Jordan|date=3 February 2021|title=H.E.R., Sia, and Trent Reznor lead 2021 Golden Globes nominations|url=https://www.thefader.com/2021/02/03/her-sia-and-trent-reznor-2021-golden-globes-nominations|access-date=6 February 2021|website=[[The Fader|The FADER]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Horton|first=Adrian|date=2021-03-01|title=The full list of Golden Globes 2021 winners| url=http://www.theguardian.com/film/2021/feb/28/golden-globes-2021-winners-full-list-tv-film| url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210301092805/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2021/feb/28/golden-globes-2021-winners-full-list-tv-film| archive-date=March 1, 2021| access-date=March 1, 2021| website=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> As director of ''Music'', Sia later won the [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Director]].<ref>{{Cite news|date=April 24, 2021|title=Razzies: Singer Sia named 'worst director' for controversial film Music|work=[[BBC News]]| url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-56856540| url-status=live|access-date=April 24, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210424090940/https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-56856540| archive-date=April 24, 2021}}</ref>

==Personal life==
=== Relationships and family ===
Following the disbandment of Crisp in 1997, Sia moved to London to follow her relationship with boyfriend Dan Pontifex.<ref name="FT06072014">{{cite web|url=http://www.fashiontimes.com/articles/8205/20140607/sia-furlers-mystery-fiance-revealed-singer-songwriter-engaged-american-documentary.htm |title=Sia Furler's Mystery Fiance Revealed! Singer Songwriter Is Engaged to American Documentary Maker Erik Anders Lang |date=7 June 2014 |work=Fashion Times |access-date=24 November 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125065234/http://www.fashiontimes.com/articles/8205/20140607/sia-furlers-mystery-fiance-revealed-singer-songwriter-engaged-american-documentary.htm |archive-date=25 November 2015 }}</ref> Several weeks later, while on a stopover in Thailand, she received the news that Pontifex had died after being in a car accident in London.<ref name=pagesix2021/><ref>{{Cite web|title = Dan Pontifex Award – win a scholarship to Australia|url = http://www.jancisrobinson.com/articles/dan-pontifex-award-win-a-scholarship-to-australia|website = www.jancisrobinson.com|access-date = 24 November 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151125084342/http://www.jancisrobinson.com/articles/dan-pontifex-award-win-a-scholarship-to-australia|archive-date = 25 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> She returned to Australia, but received a call from one of Pontifex's former housemates, who invited her to stay in London.<ref name="SMHSia"/> Her 2001 album ''Healing Is Difficult'' lyrically deals with Pontifex's death: "I was pretty fucked up after Dan died. I couldn't really feel anything." Sia recalled the effect of his death in a 2007 interview for ''[[The Sunday Times]]'': "We were all devastated, so we got shit-faced on drugs and [[Special Brew]]. Unfortunately, that bender lasted six years for me."<ref name=Age>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-reveals-hearbreaking-reason-she-wears-wigs-in-james-cordens-carpool-karaoke-20160218-gmxa3r.html|title=Sia reveals reason she wears wigs in James Corden's Carpool Karaoke|work=The Age|date=18 February 2016|access-date=22 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161231161605/http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-reveals-hearbreaking-reason-she-wears-wigs-in-james-cordens-carpool-karaoke-20160218-gmxa3r.html|archive-date=31 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Verrico">{{Cite news | url = http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/culture/music/article77556.ece | title = A Woman on the Verge | last1 = Verrico | first1 = Lisa | newspaper = [[The Sunday Times]] | date = 30 December 2007 | access-date = 7 July 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150114174024/http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/culture/music/article77556.ece | archive-date = 14 January 2015 | url-status=dead }}{{subscription required}}</ref>

Sia married documentary filmmaker Erik Anders Lang at her home in [[Palm Springs, California]], in August 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sia Furler gets married in US|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/latest-news/sia-furler-gets-married-in-us/story-fn3dxix6-1227012334021|work=The Australian|date=4 August 2014|access-date=4 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150117154220/http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/latest-news/sia-furler-gets-married-in-us/story-fn3dxix6-1227012334021|archive-date=17 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The couple revealed their separation in December 2016.<ref>Mizoguchi, Karen and Jeff Nelson. [http://people.com/music/sia-separates-from-husband-erik-anders-lang "Sia Separates from Husband Erik Anders Lang: 'We Are Dedicated to Remaining Friends'"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161209132452/http://people.com/music/sia-separates-from-husband-erik-anders-lang/ |date=9 December 2016 }}, ''People'' magazine, 7 December 2016</ref> During a 2014 appearance on ''[[The Howard Stern Show]]'', Sia was asked if she was religious, to which she responded, "I believe in a [[Higher Power]] and it's called 'Whatever Dude' and he's a queer, surfing Santa that's a bit like my grandpa, so yes."<ref name="10 Things">{{cite magazine |first=Greg |last=Moskovitch |url=http://musicfeeds.com.au/news/10-things-we-learned-from-sias-howard-stern-interview/ |title=10 Things We Learned From Sia's Howard Stern Interview |date=19 June 2014 |magazine=[[Music Feeds]] |access-date=5 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150316065608/http://musicfeeds.com.au/news/10-things-we-learned-from-sias-howard-stern-interview/ |archive-date=16 March 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the same interview, she stated that she is a feminist and that Whatever Dude divinely inspired the lyrics she wrote for [[Rihanna]]'s song "[[Diamonds (Rihanna song)|Diamonds]]".<ref name="10 Things" /> One of Sia's tattoos on her hand reads "Whatever Dude".<ref>Jung, E. Alex. [https://www.vulture.com/2014/05/maddie-ziegler-sia-chandelier-video-chat.html "Maddie Ziegler on Sia's 'Chandelier' Video, ''Dance Moms'', and Drew Barrymore"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160928041025/http://www.vulture.com/2014/05/maddie-ziegler-sia-chandelier-video-chat.html |date=28 September 2016 }}, [[New York (magazine)|Vulture.com]], 21 May 2014, accessed 23 September 2016</ref> Sia is a cousin of Australian [[Christian rock]] musician [[Peter Furler]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/news/beyonces-rave-review-aussie-songwriter-sia-furler/2119840/ |title=Beyonce's rave review for Aussie songwriter Sia Furler |date=19 December 2013 |publisher=Australian Regional Media |access-date=16 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618174051/http://m.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/news/beyonces-rave-review-aussie-songwriter-sia-furler/2119840/ |archive-date=18 June 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 2019, Sia adopted two boys who were aging out of the [[foster care system]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Kubota|first=Samantha|date=2020-05-21|title=Sia opens up about adopting 2 teenage sons|url=https://www.today.com/parents/sia-opens-about-adopting-2-teenage-sons-t182056|access-date=2020-05-20|website=TODAY.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.instyle.com/celebrity/sia-on-motherhood | title=Sia Adopted Two Teen Sons — and They Changed Her Life Forever|magazine=InStyle|date=13 October 2020|first=Jennifer|last=Ferrise|access-date=13 October 2020}}</ref> In 2020, Sia announced that she had become a grandmother when one of her two 19-year-old sons had fathered twins.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Owoseje|first=Toyin|date=2020-07-01|title=Sia, 44, becomes grandmother after teenage son welcomes 'two babies'|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/07/01/entertainment/sia-grandmother-adopted-son-two-babies-intl-scli/index.html|access-date=2020-07-01|website=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.kiddomag.com.au/news/sia-is-a-grandmother-at-44| title=Adelaide born Sia is a grandmother at 44|magazine=Kiddo|date=2 July 2020|first=Olivia|last=Williams|access-date=28 August 2020}}</ref>

=== Sexuality ===
In 2008, Sia discussed her sexual orientation in interviews<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kregloe|first1=Karman|title=Sia's Coming Out|url=http://www.afterellen.com/people/29001-sias-coming-out|access-date=18 January 2015|work=[[AfterEllen.com]]|date=10 February 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118085457/http://www.afterellen.com/people/29001-sias-coming-out|archive-date=18 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and revealed her relationship with [[JD Samson]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/guides/summer/2010/66785/|title=Sia, the Power Balladist Who Wants to Party|last=Murphy|first=Tim|date=20 June 2010|website=NYMag.com|access-date=22 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315072214/http://nymag.com/guides/summer/2010/66785/|archive-date=15 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> they broke up in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jeffs|first1=Lotte|title=Hit girl Sia ... the singer who writes Rihanna and Jessie J's chart-toppers|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/hit-girl-sia--the-singer-who-writes-rihanna-and-jessie-js-charttoppers-8319507.html|access-date=18 January 2015|work=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=16 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119020133/http://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/hit-girl-sia--the-singer-who-writes-rihanna-and-jessie-js-charttoppers-8319507.html|archive-date=19 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sia, J.D. Samson Confirm Split|url=http://www.advocate.com/news/daily-news/2011/06/13/sia-jd-samson-split|access-date=18 January 2015|work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|date=13 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104030344/http://www.advocate.com/news/daily-news/2011/06/13/sia-jd-samson-split|archive-date=4 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> When asked about her sexuality in 2009, she said, "I've always dated boys and girls and anything in between. I don't care what gender you are, it's about people. ... I've always been... well, flexible is the word I would use."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.samesame.com.au/25/2009/SiaFurler |title=Sia Furler: The Same Same 25, the 25 Most Influential Gay and Lesbian Australians |work=samesame.com.au |year=2009 |access-date=30 September 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224055513/http://www.samesame.com.au/25/2009/SiaFurler |archive-date=24 February 2017 }}</ref> Sia identified as [[queer]] on Twitter in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/25-essential-lgbtq-pride-songs-199348/sia-alive-2016-193704/ |title=25 Essential LGBTQ Pride Songs |last1=Portwood |first1=Jerry |last2= Exposito |first2=Suzy |last3=Sheffield |first3=Rob |date=2019-06-01 |website=RollingStone.com |access-date=2020-10-19}}</ref>

=== Mental health and substance use ===
Sia has suffered from depression, addictions to painkillers and alcohol. In 2010, she wrote a suicide note, planning to [[Drug overdose|overdose]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Knopper|first1=Steve|title=Sia Furler, the Socially Phobic Pop Star|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html?_r=0|access-date=18 January 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=18 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129165206/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html?_r=0|archive-date=29 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> A friend phoned her and, unintentionally, saved her life.<ref name=pagesix2021>{{Cite web|last=Kaplan|first=Michael|date=27 February 2021|title=Who is Sia? Inside the singer's weird world|url=https://pagesix.com/article/who-is-sia-inside-the-singers-weird-world/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210227215300/https://pagesix.com/article/who-is-sia-inside-the-singers-weird-world/|archive-date=27 February 2021|access-date=13 March 2021|website=[[New York Post#Page Six|Page Six]]}}</ref> Following this, Sia joined [[Alcoholics Anonymous]].<ref>{{Cite news| last=Angelini|first=Francesca|date=11 February 2021|title=Sia on making the move into directing and her first film, Music|work=[[The Times]]| url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/songwriter-sia-on-the-move-into-directing-and-her-first-film-music-rwwxm3s0x|access-date=13 March 2021|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> Sia cancelled various promotional events and shows due to her poor health in 2010.<ref name="SiaStop">{{cite web| url=http://www.siamusic.net/news-blogs/important-sia-announcement|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100628081118/http://www.siamusic.net/news-blogs/important-sia-announcement|title=*** important sia announcement ***|archive-date=28 June 2010|work=siamusic.net}}</ref> She cited extreme lethargy and panic attacks and considered retiring permanently from performing and touring. She stated that she had been diagnosed with [[Graves' disease]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-furler-fame-does-not-become-her-20100617-yjdr.html|title=Sia Furler: Fame does not become her|work=[[The Age]]|first=Andrew|last=Murfett|date=18 June 2010|access-date=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150108204138/http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-furler-fame-does-not-become-her-20100617-yjdr.html|archive-date=8 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Later that year, Sia said her health was improving after rest and thyroid hormone replacement therapy.<ref name="JJJInterview">{{cite web| url=http://www.inertia-music.com/2010/10/stream-sia-chats-about-aria-awards-recovery-and-pop-stardom|title=Sia Chats About ARIA Awards|publisher=Inertia Music|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110311001119/http://www.inertia-music.com/2010/10/stream-sia-chats-about-aria-awards-recovery-and-pop-stardom/|archive-date=11 March 2011}}</ref> In 2019, Sia stated that she suffers from [[Ehlers–Danlos syndromes|Ehlers–Danlos syndrome]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.medpagetoday.com/blogs/celebritydiagnosis/82650?eun=g1256810d0r|title=Pop Star Sia Opens Up About Her Chronic Pain|website=[[MedPage Today]]|last1=Berman|first1=Michele R.|last2=Boguski|first2=Mark S.|author-link2=Mark Boguski|date=10 October 2019|access-date=13 October 2019}}</ref> and in 2020, she stated that she has been diagnosed with [[complex post-traumatic stress disorder]], stemming from childhood traumas, including being sexually abused at the age of nine.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Sia: Nine things we learned when she spoke to Louis Theroux|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/3xRp7dXFv3YMQjB4YylgsvW/sia-nine-things-we-learned-when-she-spoke-to-louis-theroux|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201212102740/https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/3xRp7dXFv3YMQjB4YylgsvW/sia-nine-things-we-learned-when-she-spoke-to-louis-theroux|archive-date=12 December 2020|access-date=13 March 2021|publisher=[[BBC Radio 4]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Atad|first=Corey|date=1 July 2020|title=Sia Opens Up About Dealing With PTSD And Suicidal Thoughts|url=https://etcanada.com/news/663199/sia-opens-up-about-dealing-with-ptsd-and-suicidal-thoughts/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201213073347/https://etcanada.com/news/663199/sia-opens-up-about-dealing-with-ptsd-and-suicidal-thoughts/|archive-date=13 December 2020|access-date=13 March 2021|website=[[Entertainment Tonight Canada|ET Canada]]}}</ref>

==Animal activism==
Sia "has long been an advocate for animals".<ref name=PuppiesAre>[https://www.looktothestars.org/news/17417-aspca-and-sia-puppies-are-forever "ASPCA and Sia – 'Puppies Are Forever'"], LooktotheStars.org, 7 December 2017, accessed 7 August 2020</ref> She has participated in campaigns to protest against large-scale pet breeding and encourage people to spay or neuter their pets.<ref>Le Vine, Lauren. [https://www.refinery29.com/en-us/2016/01/101625/sia-furler-bio-facts#slide-3 "22 Things You Never Knew About Sia"], Refinery29.com, 27 January 2016, accessed 6 August 2020</ref><ref>[https://www.billboard.com/photos/6465902/musicians-posing-for-peta-ads "Musicians Who've Posed for PETA (and Sometimes Stripped Down): Pink, Sia and More"], ''Billboard'', 13 May 2015, accessed 6 August 2020</ref> She performed her song "I'm in Here" at the Beagle Freedom Project Gala, in 2013,<ref>Chase, Kevin. [https://web.archive.org/web/20150209135123/http://www.beaglefreedomproject.org/meet_the_hollywood_hound "Meet the Hollywood Hounds!"], Beagle Freedom Project, 7 May 2014, archived 9 February 2015</ref><ref>{{cite web |author1=Beagle Freedom Project |title=Sia Furler Performs at Beagle Freedom Project Gala |website=[[YouTube]] |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ixf_PfZuFlg  |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211222/ixf_PfZuFlg |archive-date=2021-12-22 |url-status=live|access-date=8 August 2020 |date=22 May 2014}}{{cbignore}}</ref> and wrote the song "Free the Animal" for [[public service announcement]]s supporting "cruelty-free ... fashion" in 2015.<ref>Donnelley, Matthew Scott. [https://popcrush.com/sia-peta-free-the-animal "Sia's 'Free the Animal' Soundtracks PETA's Surreal Campaign"], Popcrush.com, 23 November 2015, accessed 7 August 2020</ref> For her 2016 [[Nostalgic for the Present Tour]], Sia partnered with various rescue organisations to conduct a dog adoption fair at each of her concerts.<ref name=PuppiesAre/><ref>Getz, Dana. [https://www.bustle.com/p/sias-free-me-video-raises-awareness-for-important-cause-with-help-from-zoe-saldana-julianne-moore-63494 "Sia's 'Free Me' Video Has a Powerful Message"], Bustle.com, 9 June 2017, accessed 6 August 2020</ref> In 2017, she released another public service announcement to encourage pet adoption.<ref name=PuppiesAre/> She is a narrator of the animal rights documentary ''[[Dominion (2018 film)|Dominion]]''.<ref>Pritchett, Liam. [https://www.livekindly.co/scariest-movie-ever-vegan-documentary "The Scariest Movie Ever Made Is a Vegan Documentary"], LiveKindly.co, 30 August 2019, accessed 7 August 2020</ref>

